<br />
<h3>About HIER</h3>
<div class="row">
  <div class="span12">
  <h4>Overview</h4>
  <p>
	Health informatics is about using computers to enhance the way health information is processed, and there are three aspects of health informatics that can be identifed: healthcare, information, software. Within each of these areas, there are different documents outlining ethical obligations. HIER is an attempt to index and catalog these diverse documents to gain new insights and start new conversations about the area of health/medical informatics ethics.
  </p>
  <h4>People</h4>
  <p>
  HIER is created and maintained by <a href="http://hwsamuel.com" target="_blank">Hamman Samuel</a>, a doctoral student at the <a href="http://cs.ualberta.ca" target="_blank">University of Alberta</a>, Edmonton, Canada, under the supervision of <a href="http://webdocs.cs.ualberta.ca/~zaiane/" target="_blank">Dr. Osmar Zaiane</a>. 
  HIER is envisioned as a searchable index of public-domain codes of ethics as well as technical standards related to health informatics. 
  The aim of the project is to provide an easy lookup reference for researchers in the field of health informatics ethics.
  </p>
  <h4>Publications</h4>
  <p>
  The following peer-reviewed publications are outcomes of our research.
  <ul>
		<li>Hamman W. Samuel, Osmar R. Zaiane, Dick Sobsey. <b>Towards a Definition of Health Informatics Ethics</b>. <i>In Proceedings of 1st ACM International Health Informatics Symposium, IHI '10</i>. Arlington, VA, USA, Nov 2010. <a href="http://hwsamuel.com/wp-content/uploads/acmihi2010.pdf" target="_blank">[Download]</a></li>
  </ul>
	</p>
